frameDefinitions: These are words relating to filling containers and covering areas with some thing, things or substance, the Theme.
The words in this frame describe situations in which an Agent or a Cause injures a Victim.
The words in this frame refer to what Clothing the Wearer (or a specific Body_part of the Wearer) has on.
An Assailant physically attacks a Victim (which is usually but not always sentient), causing or intending to cause the Victim physical damage.
An Exerter, Action, or Force is capable of exerting or does exert a physical force at a level specified by the target.
A Wearer puts on an item of Clothing, which then occupies the Body_location.
frameExamples: Lionel Hutz <t>coated</t> the wall with paint.
Rod saw his father <t>beating</t> his mother.
I <t>had</t> <t>on</t> the most ridiculous monkey-suit you could imagine.
As soon as he stepped out of the bar he was <t>set</t> upon by four men in ski-masks.
Eugenie loved the sea and was a <t>strong</t> swimmer.
You didn't have to <t>dress</t> like a pirate to impress me. INI
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> is the actor who instigates the filling.
The <fen>Theme</fen> is the physical object or substance which changes location.
The <fen>Goal</fen> is the area or container being filled. Goal is generally the NP Object in this frame.
An event which brings about the filling of the <fen>Goal</fen>.
When the filling occurs.
Where the filling takes place.
<fen>Agent</fen> is the person causing the <fen>Victim</fen>'s injury.

The <fen>Victim</fen> is the being or entity that is injured.  If the <fen>Victim</fen> is included in the phrase indicating <fen>Body_part</fen>, the <fen>Victim</fen> role is tagged on a second role layer (see 3rd example).
The <fen>Body_part</fen> identifies the location on the body where the bodily injury takes place.
The <fen>Cause</fen> marks expressions that indicate some non-intentional, typically non-human, force that inflicts harm on the <fen>Victim</fen>
<fen>Time</fen> identifies the time when the harm-causing event occurs.
<fen>Place</fen> identifies the place where the harm causing event occurs.
The person whose clothing is under discussion.
This role identifies the <fen>Clothing</fen> that the <fen>Wearer</fen> wears.
The body part of the <fen>Wearer</fen> which is covered by the <fen>Clothing</fen>.
The time at or during which the <fen>Wearer</fen> has the <fen>Clothing</fen> on.
This role is the being or entity that is injured by the <fen>Assailant</fen>'s attack.
The person (or other self-directed entity) that is attempting physical harm to the <fen>Victim</fen>.
This role identifies the time when the <fen>Assailant</fen> attacks the <fen>Victim</fen>.
This role identifies the place where the <fen>Assailant</fen> makes an assault on the <fen>Victim</fen>.
The <fen>Exerter</fen> that can or does exert a force of the level specified by the target.
The <fen>Force</fen> that can or does exert a force of the level specified by the target.
The <fen>Action</fen> that can or does exert a force of the level specified by the target.
The <fen>Time</fen> during which the <fen>Exerter</fen>, <fen>Action</fen>, or <fen>Force</fen> can or does exert its force.
The location where the <fen>Exerter</fen>, <fen>Action</fen>, or <fen>Force</fen> can or does exert its force.
The individual that puts <fen>Clothing</fen> on their body.
<fen>Clothing</fen> is used for the item of clothing that the <fen>Wearer</fen> ends up wearing.
The time when the <fen>Wearer</fen> puts an item of <fen>Clothing</fen> on.
The <fen>Place</fen> indicates where the Donning occurs.
